Parent status: In Progress
Parent summary: We need to improve our speed as well as the quality of work for our submission to the inocrowd animal welfare monitoring system challenge. Below and attached are details about the challenge, for reference/refresh your memory. I've already started work on it, and the prototype is in development, but the submission is due soon and we need to pick up the pace, and do a better job of delivering a quality solution that meets/exceeds the requirements of the challenge. So need to group work into chunks that can be worked on in tandem/parallel, and figure out the best roles to handle each chunk of work and get agents started working on it. So please help me figure out how we can break up/organize the necessary work, and let me know good roles/agent skills that would be appropriate for each grouping of work. Then I/we can start delegating the work.

Attached are files about the challenge, and here is the summary of the challenge:

Advanced and Predictive Monitoring of Animal Welfare in a Dairy Cattle Production Unit.
Description
The central issue is to develop a system capable of continuously, objectively and predictively monitoring animal welfare in dairy cattle production units, integrating behavioural, biomechanical, physiological, environmental and cow handling parameters.

Details of the Challenge
The challenge is to overcome the limitations of traditional methods and existing certification standards, which only provide sporadic and subjective information, ensuring integrated monitoring of the performance of production units and serving as a robust basis for operational and strategic decision-making.

The assessment of animal welfare in dairy production units is currently based on on-site audits and isolated technological systems (e.g. collars, thermal cameras, environmental sensors), which only provide sporadic information. Seeker aims to evolve into a continuous, objective and predictive monitoring model, capable of anticipating risks and supporting management decisions.

      The challenge is to develop an integrated solution that collects and interprets behavioural, biomechanical, physiological and environmental data from animals, enabling early identification of signs of stress, pain, disease, thermal discomfort, locomotor problems and irregularities in cow handling. The solution should issue alerts, propose corrective actions and provide an intuitive and standardised dashboard.

The solution must integrate data from multiple technological sources (sensors, cameras, monitoring devices such as collars, and already implemented systems), have risk prediction capabilities, and adapt to different layouts of dairy production units. The solution should allow for a pilot project in one production unit and subsequently be scalable to around 1,000 production units spread across two European countries.

The aim is therefore for Solver to propose a solution based on the development of a comprehensive Digital Twin of the dairy production unit, dynamically and integrally incorporating behavioural, biomechanical, physiological, environmental and management dimensions, applying advanced computer vision technologies, multivariate data analysis and artificial intelligence.

The ultimate goal is to develop a solution that is reliable, scalable and autonomous, providing standardised and actionable information to producers and veterinarians, promoting continuous improvement in management practices and ensuring the sustainability and quality of milk, as well as production efficiency.                   

The advanced technical details (including biomechanical, physiological, environmental, and behavioural domains) are found in Annex I, which should be considered for guidance, without prejudice to the Solver's creativity in defining the final architecture.

In Annex II, you will find the context of the limitations of existing methods and the strategic motivation for the challenge.

The solution should contribute to:

·         Increased animal welfare in milk production units;

·         Improving milk quality;

·         Increased production efficiency and cost reduction;

·         Mitigating health and production risks;

·         Strengthening environmental sustainability and ESG performance in the primary milk sector;

·         Greater appreciation of milk and consumer confidence;

·         Competitive differentiation and intellectual property potential;

The main expectation is the creation of a comprehensive Digital Twin of the production unit, which accurately represents the behavioural, biomechanical, physiological and environmental dimensions of the cattle herd, ensuring permanent monitoring and the ability to predict risks that impact animal health and milk production performance in production units. Through this dynamic digital representation, Seeker intends to evolve from a reactive model to a preventive model, supported by artificial intelligence and machine learning, capable of anticipating events that could compromise animal welfare and production performance.

Expected Solution
With this challenge, Seeker aims to develop an advanced technological solution that will transform the current animal welfare assessment model into an intelligent, continuous, predictive and scientifically based system capable of generating a direct impact on milk quality, the productivity of milk production units and the sustainability of the entire value chain.

Seeker expects this solution to lead to significant gains in raw material quality, improved production rates and extended cow life, while reducing operating costs, disease incidence and waste associated with reactive management.

Ultimately, the goal is to position Seeker as a national and international benchmark in the digitisation of animal welfare and sustainable milk production, strengthening consumer confidence and creating conditions for future patents and competitive advantages in the agri-food sector.

Seeker expects a solution that:

Mandatory features

·         Monitors animal welfare indicators 24/7;

·         Integrates data from sensors, cameras or external sources;

·         Presents dashboards with indicators per animal and per dairy production unit;

·         Generates automatic alerts when deviations from normal occur;

·         Propose corrective actions based on data and scientific evidence;

·         Include predictive capabilities (early risk identification);

Minimum expected outputs

·         Central dashboard with animal welfare indicators;

·         Alert and recommendation system;

·         Daily/weekly risk report;

·         Technical plan for scaling up to 1,000 dairy production units;

·         Proposed solution architecture.

Valued

·         Ability to incorporate advanced modules (3D locomotion, automatic Quantitative Behaviour Assessment (QBA), heat stress analysis, social behaviour, rumination and calf adaptation);

·         Automatic adaptation to different layouts of dairy production units;

·         Integration with existing commercial systems;

·         Creativity.

Seeker will also value the following requirements:

Data Quality, Security and Privacy Requirements

·         Ensure data security, confidentiality and protection at all stages;

·         Ensure backups, integrity and auditability of information;

·         Ensure a high level of reliability in data storage, processing and transmission.

Deliverables and Solution Demonstration Requirements

·         Include proof of concept (PoC) or actual functional demonstration;

·         Present a clear development plan (phases, team, resources, KPIs);

·         Demonstrate consistent integration between all modules of the solution.

Strategic Alignment Requirements with the Seeker

·         Demonstrate direct impact on raw material quality and production performance;

·         Support the digitisation, sustainability and traceability of the dairy sector;

·         Identify intellectual property potential associated with the solution.

Proposals will be excluded if they:

·        Lack scientific or technological justification;

·        Lack of integration with existing systems;

·        Inability to ensure continuous and predictive monitoring;

·        Do not include behavioural, biomechanical, physiological and environmental dimensions;

·        Lack of artificial intelligence with self-learning capabilities;

·        Lack of scenario planning and decision support capabilities;

·        Non-compliance with security, privacy, and data protection requirements;

·        Operational impracticability or disproportionate cost;

·        Lack of practical applicability to the dairy sector;

·        Lack of demonstration or absence of proof of concept.

All proposals that do not guarantee technological rigour, scientific basis, data integration, continuous monitoring, advanced artificial intelligence and measurable impact on milk production and quality will be excluded, as well as all those that are not aligned with Seeker's strategy of sustainability, innovation and competitiveness.

Minimum Requirements
Demonstrate experience in AI, computer vision or sensor integration;
Present a scalable solution for hundreds of units;
Integrate existing data sources in dairy production units;
Ensure continuous monitoring and alert generation;
Ensure compliance with data protection standards;
Present a plan for a pilot to start in the last quarter of 2026;
Deliver schedule, team and technical methodology.
Areas
SustainabilityIndustrial EngineeringArtificial IntelligenceInformation TechnologyData ScienceMachine LearningTelecommunicationsAgro EngineeringMedicineEnvironment Engineering
Deadline
April 27, 2026 6:59 PM

